definition: Really good or impressive (often used for music).
The overall look, vibe, or visual style of something or someone.
Abbreviation for "address." (e.g., "Send me the addy for the party.")
Extremely excited or energized.
To perform exceptionally well; to completely conquer something. (e.g., "She ate that presentation, no crumbs left.")
The distinctive atmosphere or quality that seems to surround and be generated by a person, thing, or place. Often used in relation to someone's perceived energy.
Short for "before anyone else"; a term of endearment for a romantic partner or close friend.
Obvious, easily noticeable, or suspicious (often in a negative context, like "that's bait" meaning "that's too obvious/risky").
Very, a lot, many, or plenty of. (e.g., "I've got bare work to do," "she's bare pretty.")
Someone or something unoriginal, mainstream, and predictable.
Spending extended periods of time in bed, often on devices, avoiding responsibilities.
An argument or conflict.
A personality trait or habit that is neither good nor bad, but just... there. (A humorous take on "red flags" and "green flags" in relationships.)
An affirmation; meaning "yes," "okay," "agreed," or "for sure."
Acronym for "Be For Real." Used to express disbelief or skepticism, or to demand seriousness.
An exclamation of extreme embarrassment or dismay; something very awkward.
An excellent performance or achievement (e.g., "he pulled a blinder").
The number of sexual partners someone has had.
A really good song; a catchy tune.
Being in a romantic relationship with someone.
An exclamation used when something is done quickly, suddenly, or successfully.
Luxurious, high-class, or fancy, often with a hint of pretentiousness.
The idea that one's brain is "rotting" from consuming too much stimulating but often nonsensical online content.
Coined by Charli XCX's 2024 album, refers to an aesthetic of genuine, self-possessed, non-conforming, rebellious, and effortlessly cool energy.
A versatile exclamation expressing surprise, disbelief, frustration, or general camaraderie.
Tired, drained, or exhausted (similar to "knackered").
Attractive, muscular (often used for men). Can also mean "good" or "impressive."
Extremely good or delicious, often used for food. (e.g., "This pizza is bussin'!")
Very excited or happy.
Refers to a pivotal or defining moment in someone's life, often humorous and implying it's unavoidable (from "Spider-Man: Across the Spider-Verse").
A lie or falsehood.
No lie; telling the truth, genuinely. (Strong ties to hip-hop culture, very popular in the US.)
Caught definitively doing something wrong, with clear evidence, like a high-resolution photo or video.
Outdated, uncool, or trying too hard to be trendy, especially for millennials. (Was very popular in 2021-2022, still understood.)
Relaxed, calm, or easygoing. Can also mean "hang out."
To flirt or chat up someone.
Very pleased or happy. (Still widely used, but often by younger generations too.)
Someone who spends an excessive amount of time on the internet and whose thoughts/behaviors are heavily influenced by online culture.
To vomit. (Older slang, but still understood and used by some.)
Can mean very ugly or unattractive (often used harshly for people), or broken/worn out for objects.
A swift, witty, and often sassy retort or comeback to an insult or criticism.
Influence, fame, or popularity, especially on social media.
The act of employees briefly showing up at their physical workplace, usually in the morning, to interact with coworkers before leaving (new WFH/hybrid work term).
Exhausted, done for, or in trouble.
Used dismissively to end an argument; similar to "deal with it."
Short for "Cost of Living Crisis" (a particularly British preoccupation right now).
Good, impressive, skilled (often used for a person's ability).
To get mad or upset despite better judgment, often leading to reckless decisions. (Originates from African American communities.)
Laughing very hard.
Content or behavior that is embarrassing, awkward, or uncomfortable to witness, often inducing second-hand embarrassment.
Being both drunk and high at the same time.
To reject or ignore someone's romantic advances.
Excellent, high quality, or exceptionally cool (often for memes or cannabis).
Something or someone that is basic, uninteresting, or boring (often for a person).
Extremely amused or overwhelmed by something (like "I'm dead from laughing").
Being completely serious, truthful, or honest.
Short for "delusional"; holding unrealistic or excessively idealistic beliefs, often humorously.
Encouraging risky or spontaneous behavior for the sake of an interesting story or experience, often for social media.
Doing well, being successful, or achieving good things.
The act of consuming endless negative news or social media content, leading to feelings of anxiety and dread.
Desperate for a relationship or attention.
To seek out and publish private information online about someone, usually with malicious intentions.
To mock or humiliate someone, often publicly.
A person's stylish, fashionable, or cool sense of clothing and overall appearance.
A style subculture, often associated with specific fashion, internet presence, and sometimes a more alternative or melancholic aesthetic.
Sleepy (often used humorously).
Acronym for "Explain Like I'm 5" (meaning explain it simply).
A distinct period in one's life characterized by specific interests, activities, or priorities (e.g., "I'm in my villain era").
Over-the-top, overly dramatic, or excessive in behavior or appearance.
Referring to one's attractive face, often implying it's so good it "never declines."
Short for "family"; refers to close friends or one's inner circle.
An emphatic way of saying "facts" or "that's undeniably true," implying no further explanation is needed.
Acting wildly, uncontrollably, or without inhibition (often humorously).
To emphasize agreement or sincerity.
Skillfully manipulating a situation to one's advantage, often in a clever or subtle way.
Short for "fixing to"; going to, or about to. (Rooted in Southern American English).
Something extremely good, cool, or impressive.
A "fake Instagram" account, often used for more private or unfiltered content shared with a smaller group of close friends.
Short for "outfit"; a quick display or assessment of one's attire.
To show off or boast about possessions, skills, or achievements.
The opposite of a "bop"; something that is unsuccessful or bad.
A period of being unsuccessful or in a rut.
Acronym for "Fear Of Missing Out"; anxiety that an exciting or interesting event may currently be happening elsewhere.
A party or social gathering (e.g., "pulling up to the function").
Shocked, amazed, or left speechless (often in a positive way).
Clothes, garments.
To hype someone up; to encourage or compliment enthusiastically.
Excited, hyped up, or overly confident. (Can also mean smelling of gas if used literally!)
To abruptly end all communication with someone, especially in dating or friendships, without explanation.
A collection of snacks or random foods eaten as a casual meal, often posted on social media.
A humorous justification for spending money that makes purchases seem logical or free (e.g., "If I return this, it's free money for that").
To excessively praise or flatter someone, often to an annoying degree or for personal gain.
A hot dog.
A significant improvement in one's appearance, confidence, or overall life.
The opposite of a "glow up"; a negative transformation in appearance or well-being.
Mouth (e.g., "shut your gob").
Acronym for "Greatest Of All Time."
A positive, healthy, or desirable trait or behavior in a person or situation.
Acronym for "Get Ready With Me"; a common social media video format where someone films their routine.
(Derogatory) A term for old people (less common but does exist).
Good, cool, or excellent; everything is fine.
Extremely disappointed or upset. (Classic, still current.)
A group of female friends (often used interchangeably with "girlies").
Having a difficult or frustrating time.
Very, extremely (more common in some UK regions, like Liverpool, influenced by US usage).
Openly, obviously, or intensely; the opposite of "low-key."
Something that has a unique, more profound, or better impact than usual.
"Take this loss"; a dismissive way to tell someone they've failed.
A period of embracing self-confidence, freedom, and enjoyment, particularly for women.
One hundred percent; absolutely sure.
(Derogatory) A variation of "hoes," used to objectify or belittle women (popularized by some streamers).
A sudden feeling of disgust or repulsion towards someone you were previously attracted to.
Acronym for "I just burst out laughing." (Online/text slang.)
Used to express that one is acting childlike or needs to be babied.
Short for "isn't it?"; used to seek agreement or confirm something. (Very common across all ages in the UK.)
An exclamation used to express shock, embarrassment, or amusement.
Used to describe the vibe or impression something provides (e.g., "It's giving main character energy").
Acronym for "If You Know, You Know"; refers to an inside joke or shared understanding.
A pejorative term for an obnoxious, angry, or entitled middle-aged white woman.
Short for "loss"; represents failure, something bad, or a defeat.
To run away quickly.
See "Ate"; performed so perfectly that nothing was left to be desired.
A stylized way of saying "looks," referring to a person's fashionable outfit or appearance.
To meet up with someone.
When something occupies your thoughts constantly; you can't stop thinking about it.
A state of total concentration on a task; completely focused.
An attempt to maximize physical attractiveness, often through various (sometimes pseudoscientific) methods.
The backstory or context behind something, often niche or humorous, or the narrative surrounding a person/event.
Secretly, subtly, or somewhat; keeping something discreet.
Someone who acts like they are the protagonist of their own life story, often with a sense of self-importance or a desire to be the center of attention.
A group of male friends.
Short for "mental breakdown."
Mediocre, average, or disappointing.
Disgusting, unattractive, or smelly.
Excellent, fantastic, great. (More common in the North of England, but understood broadly.)
To look significantly more attractive than someone else, making them appear inferior in comparison.
Used to express that something is relatable or perfectly describes one's current emotional state.
Short for "mutuals"; people who follow each other on social media.
Excellent, awesome, very good.
A person whose success in a certain field (especially entertainment) is perceived to be due to their famous or well-connected parents.
A novice or inexperienced person, especially in gaming.
Acronym for "Non-Player Character"; someone who lacks individuality, critical thinking, or is just following the crowd.
An exclamation of discomfort, sympathy, or acknowledgment of a difficult situation.
A dismissive retort to an older person perceived as being out of touch or condescending.
Perfectly executed, flawless, or on point (often used for appearance).
Acronym for "One Of My Followers/Friends" (on social media).
Short for "opponent"; refers to a rival or enemy.
Can mean unfortunate, annoying, or bad ("That's peak, innit?"). Also can mean the best/ultimate point of something.
Attractive, appealing, or delicious. (Can be used for people, food, or things.)
An attractive person (often female).
An emphatic way of ending a statement, adding emphasis and finality.
Someone who craves attention and approval, often by putting others down or trying to differentiate themselves from their peers.
Good, cool, high quality (often for drugs, but can be generally applied).
Someone who can provide something, often illicit or hard to get (e.g., "he's the plug for concert tickets").
An affectionate term for a loved one, usually romantic.
Acronym for "Point Of View"; often used to set the scene for a relatable scenario.
Very, genuinely, or intensely. (e.g., "That was proper good.")
Doing the bare minimum at work; fulfilling job responsibilities but not going above and beyond.
When a reply to a post gets significantly more likes than the original post, indicating widespread disapproval of the original.
Proof or evidence, often in the form of screenshots or documented interactions.
A warning sign or characteristic that indicates a problematic or undesirable situation or person.
Someone who frequently replies to tweets, often with unsolicited or unhelpful comments.
Short for "charisma"; the ability to charm, flirt with, or attract someone. (Oxford's word of the year 2023).
A young person, typically male, associated with urban street culture. (The term itself has a specific UK connotation.)
Good, alright, cool, or okay. (Very versatile, often used as a greeting or agreement.)
Feeling bitter, annoyed, or jealous.
Bold, fearless, exceptionally cool, or delivering a harsh but clever comeback.
Making me laugh extremely hard.
Extremely tired or exhausted.
An exclamation of surprise, amazement, or excitement.
To support a romantic relationship between two fictional characters or real people.
Deeply shocked, surprised, or amazed.
A look of disapproval, skepticism, or judgment.
Someone who is independent, self-reliant, and often rejects social norms; a lone wolf.
Someone who shows excessive attention, adoration, or submissiveness towards someone they like, often in an unreciprocated way.
A knife or weapon (more specific to urban slang).
A nonsensical term popularized by a viral YouTube series, often used humorously to describe something chaotic or absurd.
To perform exceptionally well, succeed, or look incredibly good.
To be ignorant of or underestimate something or someone's value.
To heavily criticize or badmouth someone or something.
Looking incredibly stylish, attractive, or put-together.
A person who is very attractive.
Share the gossip or juicy information.
A group of close friends.
An obsessive and highly dedicated fan of a celebrity, musician, or public figure (derived from "stalker" + "fan").
Short for "suspicious"; something or someone untrustworthy or questionable.
Used to say that good and bad things balance each other out over time.
Gossip, juicy information, or secrets.
Acronym for "That Feeling When..." (used to describe relatable situations).
Desperate for attention, approval, or sex (often online).
A photo or video posted to gain attention or compliments, often implying sexual desire.
To have a tantrum or a fit of bad temper.
A reminder to go outside and disconnect from the internet or screens.
A burner phone; an older-style, cheap phone often used for illicit activities or by those wanting to remain discreet.
Emotionally provoked or upset by something.
To trust or believe in someone.
Excited or partying hard (often used in the context of being under the influence of alcohol/drugs).
Wild, unpredictable, or completely over-the-top behavior.
Not to be taken seriously; joking or lighthearted.
Mundane, dull, or lacking excitement.
A setting in some messaging apps where messages disappear after being viewed.
An assessment of someone's mood or the general atmosphere.
Being in sync with or enjoying the same energy as someone or something.
Short for "win"; represents success, victory, or something positive.
Short for "What's going on?"; a greeting. (Often associated with Caribbean influence in UK cities.)
Uncool, boring, or lacking excitement.
Being aware of and sensitive to social and political issues, especially racial justice.
To talk excessively or annoyingly.
An enthusiastic affirmation, often used to express excitement or approval.
To be glamorized, overdone, or made fabulous in an over-the-top way (from drag culture, now widespread).
A versatile term that can be an exclamation of excitement, a sound made while throwing something forcefully, or a random filler word.
An exclamation of discomfort, surprise, or embarrassment.
A young person or youth.
